courses.learning_outcomes:
After taking this course, students will be able to
• demonstrate the knowledge and understand the principles and practices of acquiring knowledge and solving problems through research;
• use various research methods in examining a topic in sports and exercise science;
• employ online databases for academic research;
• analyze and evaluate the quality of studies published in peer-reviewed journals

• To apply the knowledge and theories in scientific research to critically evaluate research projects;
• To present research ideas & methodology, with support of relevant literature and rationales in an effective and systematic manner;
• To generate realistic and feasible research projects through collaborative resources and partnership.

courses.course_syllabus:
• Discussion on scientific approach of knowledge exploration;
• Understanding and reflection of quantitative research design and interpretation;
• Understanding and reflection of qualitative research design and interpretation;
• Appreciation of research methodologies in other disciplines
• Communication of various research problems as it related to internal and external validity, as well as reliability;
• Selection of appropriate outcome measures, discussion on pros and cons, and practical consideration;
• Acquire knowledge and skills in performing professional academic presentation and communication

courses.learning_outcomes:
After taking this course, students will be able to --
• identify major disciplines and elements of physical fitness tests;
• stratify exercise participants into risk categories;
• perform pre-exercise screening and preparation procedures;
• perform physical fitness tests in a safe and skillful manner;
• compute metabolic demands such as exercise intensity, energy expenditure, and VO2max from various forms of exercise;
• critically evaluate the effectiveness of fitness tests in terms of validity, reliability, objectively, and practicality;
• modify fitness test protocols in order to cater the needs of different populations.

courses.course_syllabus:
• Association between physical activity, fitness, and health;
• Pre-exercise screening and risk stratification;
• Objectives and procedures of conducting health-related fitness tests;
• Test selection concern: validity, reliability, objectivity; practicality;
• Exercise testing for assessing cardiovascular fitness;
• Testing using treadmills, cycle ergometer, bench stepping;
• Laboratory and field testing protocols;
• Calculation of metabolic demands in terms of HR, VO2, and energy expenditures;
• Use and interpretation of electrocardiogram (EKG);
• Tests for assessing body composition;
• Tests for assessing muscular fitness;
• Test for assessing flexibility;
• Fitness tests for various populations – children, elderly, disciplinary officers;
• Modification of fitness tests.

courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:

• Describe mechanisms of common musculoskeletal injuries associated with sports and exercise participation;
• Manage sports injury incidents timely and appropriately;
• Describe and apply the evidence-based physical examination for common sports injuries;
• Describe and apply the conventional and routine rehabilitative procedures in managing common sports injuries;
• Distinguish the difference of medical intervention and conservative rehabilitation for common sports injuries;
• Critically inquire different types of therapeutic treatments, protective equipment, products and aids in relation to sports injury prevention and rehabilitation.

After taking this course, students will be able to --
• identify major components of health-related fitness;
• stratify exercise participants into risk categories;
• perform pre-exercise screening and preparation procedures;
• prescribe appropriate exercise prescription for healthy individual individuals and those with chronic diseases in various conditions;
• demonstrate effective communication in prescribing exercise prescription.

On completion of this course, the student will be able to:

• Demonstrate an understanding of the training requirements for different sporting populations;
• Apply a basic coaching program to effectively teach a sport skill;
• Record, review and interpret the results from a range of fitness and sports-specific testing protocols and up-to-date science and technologies;
• Identify and implement risk management strategies for the athletes’ well-being.

On completion of this course, students will be able to:
• describe the characteristics of fundamental theories of motor learning;
• identify key variables that affect motor skill learning and performance using a developmental approach;
• demonstrate an understanding of the techniques used to assess motor learning;
• discuss the practical application of the fundamental theories of motor learning; and
• review literature pertaining to motor learning critically and design a research study adheres to the scientific norms in the field.

Upon the completion of this course, students will be able to:
• understand the relationship between personality and behavior in sport and exercise;
• explore motivation and individual differences in sport and game behavior;
• investigate the major sources of stress and anxiety and how they affect performance;
• identify factors that predispose individuals to eating disorders;
• discuss different models and causes of overtraining and burnout;
• examine the aggression-performance relationship; and
• develop a physical relaxation training program.

The module aims to introduce students to the concepts of sports development, sports delivery and strategic planning for sports development; and to provide an overview of the relevant framework and techniques that can be used to analyse contemporary sports development and management issues and critically appraise sports development plans and strategies.

By the end of the course students will be able to:
• Understand the scope, purpose, principles and framework of sports development;
• Have an understanding of sports delivery systems in Hong Kong and overseas;
• Employ strategic and development planning frameworks and techniques in analyzing and addressing the development needs of sports organizations;
• Be able to critically appraise different models of strategic planning and sports development.

After taking this course, students will be able to -
• Build up their own idea in sport marketing for planning a major sports event, create strategic plan, and apply these ideas to a real-world business venture;
• Identify the contemporary concepts in sport marketing and sport sponsorships;
• Recognize the sport marketing information system;
• Understand sport sponsorship within the corporate marketing framework;
• Design a sport sponsorship proposal; and
• Develop an effective sport marketing plan, to see and seize business opportunity for planning and running a major sports event.

On completion of this course, the student will be able to:
• Demonstrate evidence and knowledge on how forms a theoretical basis for sport or exercise to achieve a critical understanding of exertion;
• Critically review the implementation of knowledge, evidence, skills and practices that are evident in the practical and professional environment;
• Reflect on personal ability to work effectively in an application or professional environment and implementing skills and practices related to sport and exercise sciences.

courses.course_syllabus:
• Planning and implementation of a professional project in disciplines of sports science and physical activity;
• Skills and knowledge of writing up a project report in a professional manner;
• Skills and knowledge of conducting professional projects in sports industry, physical activity and public health;
• Professional ethics and attitudes about working and practicing in career of sports industry, physical activity, and/or public health;
• Challenges and solutions in practicing career in sports science, physical activity, and/or public health

courses.learning_outcomes:
After taking this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate the knowledge and understand the principles and practices of acquiring knowledge and solving problems through guided research;
• critically analyze the quality of published studies;
• design a research study in a chosen area.

Following the completion of this course, the students will be able to:
• apply the knowledge and method to the investigation of a specific area within the field of exercise and sports science;
• draw upon and apply their knowledge of research methods in exercise science to integrate and further develop aspects of their taught programme;
• identify an issue to which solutions and/or recommendations can be addressed; and produce a written report which sets out clearly the aims, context, content and outcome of the exercise;
• integrate the skills and knowledge which have been taught in the degree programme with specific application to a topic to produce a well-argued report.
